timeline.bodyText:
Instead of duplicating the existing methods (using CXF's SecurityContext), maybe we could create a subclass of CXF's SecurityContext that delegates appropriately - something like:
class SecurityContextProxy implements SecurityContext {
    private final javax.ws.rs.core.SecurityContext jaxrsSecCtx;
    private final SecurityContext cxfSecCtx;
    SecurityContextProxy(javax.ws.rs.core.SecurityContext jaxrsSecCtx, SecurityContext cxfSecCtx) {
        this.jaxrsSecCtx = jaxrsSecCtx;
        this.cxfSecCtx = cxfSecCtx;
        if (jaxrsSecCtx == null && cxfSecCtx == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException();
    }

    @Override
    public Principal getUserPrincipal() {
        return jaxrsSecCtx != null ? jaxrsSecCtx.getUserPrincipal() : cxfSecCtx.getUserPrincipal();
    }

    @Override
    public boolean isUserInRole(String role) {
        return jaxrsSecCtx != null ? jaxrsSecCtx.isUserInRole(role) : cxfSecCtx.isUserInRole(role);
    }
}

This would allow you to keep the existing parse* methods and just pass an instance of this new proxy class to it - without duplicating for both SecurityContext types.

